        "id": "pe-lesson-6",
        "title": "Constraints & Guardrails",
        "description": "Constraints and guardrails are essential elements that define boundaries and prevent unwanted behaviors in AI outputs. In this lesson, we'll explore how to implement effective constraints that guide AI behavior without stifling its capabilities. Well-designed constraints ensure outputs meet specific requirements while maintaining the AI's ability to generate creative and useful responses.\n\nUnlike human communication where we assume shared understanding of boundaries and social norms, AI systems need explicit constraints to prevent them from generating inappropriate, inaccurate, or off-topic content. These constraints act as guardrails that keep the AI within acceptable parameters while allowing it to operate effectively within those boundaries.\n\nWe'll examine different types of constraints, learn how to implement them effectively, and understand how to balance restrictive requirements with creative freedom. This knowledge is crucial for creating prompts that produce reliable results in professional and public contexts.",
        "videoUrl": "",
        "content": "### Core Concept\n[object Object],[object Object],[object Object],[object Object]\n\n### Why It Matters\nConstraints and guardrails matter because AI systems don't have inherent understanding of social norms, business requirements, or content appropriateness. Without explicit constraints, AI may generate content that is technically accurate but inappropriate for the intended context, or it may hallucinate information that seems plausible but is factually incorrect.\n\nIn professional settings, constraints ensure outputs meet brand standards, legal requirements, and quality standards. They're essential when outputs will be published publicly, used for business decisions, or integrated into other systems. Poor constraint design can lead to embarrassing mistakes, legal issues, or damaged reputation.\n\nProfessional prompt engineers use constraints as tools to enhance AI effectiveness rather than limit it. Well-designed constraints channel AI capabilities toward productive outputs while preventing problematic behaviors.\n\n### Real-World Example\nConsider an AI system used to generate customer support responses. Without constraints, it might provide medical advice when asked about health-related products, give specific pricing information it doesn't have, or create responses that don't match the company's brand voice.\n\nWith effective constraints: 'You are a customer support specialist for TechCorp. Only provide information from our official documentation. If uncertain about technical details, direct customers to our support team. Do not provide medical advice, legal opinions, or specific pricing not in our documentation. Maintain a helpful, professional tone. Format responses as: Acknowledgment, Information, Next steps. Limit to 150 words.'\n\nThis constrained approach produces consistent, appropriate responses that protect the company while helping customers effectively.\n\n### Key Takeaways\nConstraints define boundaries that guide AI behavior without eliminating capabilities,Format constraints ensure outputs meet integration and consistency requirements,Negative constraints specify what to avoid, preventing inappropriate content,Hallucination prevention maintains factual accuracy in AI responses,Scope constraints ensure appropriate depth and relevance in outputs",
